{
  "doc_id": "16354",
  "text": "The second group of virulence factors encompasses proteins becoming important upon successful host colonization which in turn mediate detachment and spread within the host. This group includes mainly enzymes and nonenzymatic toxins. Hemolysins (Hla, Hlb, Hlγ) permeabilize cell membranes and lyse macrophages and lymphocytes and alter platelet morphology. Leukocidins (LukD, LukE, LukM), and Panton-Valentine leukocidin (PVL) which often associates with severe infections [CITATION_1] , form pores in leukocyte membranes which results in cell death [CITATION_2] . LukGH leukocidin enhances inflammatory response [CITATION_3] and contributes to the development of abscesses by killing the infiltrating neutrophils. Phenol soluble modulins (PSMs) are yet another type of cytolytic toxins [CITATION_4] . Exofoliative toxins (ETs -ETA, ETB, ETD) are in turn extremely specific serine proteases hydrolyzing desmoglein 1, a cadherin responsible for the integrity of cell-to-cell adhesive structures. Due to desmoglein-1 localization within the skin, the action of ETs results in skin exfoliation [CITATION_5] . Enterotoxins (SEs -SEA, SEB, SEC, SED, SEE, SEG, SEH, SEI) exhibit superantigen activity deregulating the immune system of the host.",
